{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774470751,"nonce":"vxECdO3NdNkmNoVTW0MF2i0lMGA=","title":"Memory leak in adversarial training loop: host memory grows from 57% to 96% during training","message":"## Observation\n\nDuring minimax adversarial training on v5lite TPU, host memory usage grows continuously:\n- Batch 0: 57.9%\n- Batch 250: 75.6% (after ~36 min)\n- ~10 min later: 94.2%\n- ~10 min later: 96.3%\n\nOn v4-8, memory grew more slowly (4.8% → 8.1% → 10.2% → 11.5% → 11.8%) — still growing but the v4 has much more RAM so it didn't OOM.\n\n## Context\n\nThe adversarial training loop in scripts/train_minimax.py (branch: feature/part2.5-analysis) runs:\n- Per batch: K=5 adversary inner steps (each calls _loss_and_force_grad + _adversary_update JIT functions), then 1 controller step (_controller_step JIT function)\n- Each JIT function does a 130-timestep GRU forward+backward pass\n- The adversary is updated via eqx.apply_updates (returns a new Module with different leaf values)\n\n## Why this shouldn't happen\n\nSteady-state training should use constant memory per batch:\n- Forward pass intermediates are discarded after backward pass\n- Model size is constant (apply_updates replaces leaves, doesn't grow)\n- Only accumulated data: two Python lists (adv_losses, ctrl_losses) of floats — trivially small\n- Checkpoints go to disk\n\n## Hypotheses to investigate\n\n1. **JIT recompilation cache bloat**: If eqx.filter_jit recompiles due to changing PyTree structure (e.g., adversary Module changes structure after apply_updates), each compilation is cached without freeing the previous. Check: add JAX_LOG_COMPILES=1 to see if recompilation happens every batch.\n\n2. **JAX buffer references not freed**: The stop_gradient tree traversal (jt.map creating new stopped model each batch) or force broadcast (jnp.broadcast_to each inner step) may create JAX buffers that aren't collected by GC.\n\n3. **XLA compilation artifacts**: The decomposed gradient uses two separate JIT functions called in a Python loop. Each call may allocate TPU buffers that aren't freed between calls.\n\n4. **Adversary eqx.apply_updates**: If apply_updates returns a Module with subtly different structure (e.g., optimizer state types change after first update), this would trigger recompilation + cache growth.\n\n## Diagnosis plan\n\n1. Run locally with memory profiling (jax.profiler or simple RSS tracking)\n2. Run on TPU with JAX_LOG_COMPILES=1 to detect recompilation\n3. Add explicit jax.clear_caches() every N batches to test if it's cache-related\n4. Profile with jax.live_arrays() to count live buffers over time\n5. Isolate: run just the adversary inner loop (no controller step) and see if memory still grows\n\nSession: 31fa1977\nScript: scripts/train_minimax.py (feature/part2.5-analysis branch)","files":null}]}